description:
1. Cover by Steve Bissette and John Totleben.
  2. "Revelations" written by Alan Moore, penciled by Steve Bissette, inked by John Totleben, colored by Tatjana Wood and lettered by John Costanza.

In an issue that crosses over with Crisis on Infinite Earths, Swamp Thing and John Constantine take a detour on their spiritual journey to observe the unfolding chaos on Earth. But Constantine has greater concerns: a cabal of evil beings determined to destroy all existence.

Notes:

  • First issue under the title Swamp Thing.
  • Series continues from the title The Saga of Swamp Thing.
  • Previous issue The Saga of Swamp Thing #45.
  • This issue takes place before issue #5 of Crisis on Infinite Earths and happens before issue #4.
  • There is a key death in this issue as well the answer to the question of balancing good and evil in the universe.
name: Revelations

description: Swamp Thing follows John Constantine to South America to see "The Parliament of Trees." Learning that he is not a unique being after all, Swamp Thing attempts to make sense of their wisdom, while a sleazy photographer hopes to make a fast buck with some sleazy pictures of Abigail Arcane with Swamp Thing.

description: John Constantine's assembled cohort of mystics lead Swamp Thing to a cave where a group called the Brujeria are concocting a scheme to infect the world with evil--but when Swamp Thing tries to save Constantine from their clutches, he allows one of the mystics, now transformed into a evil, bird-like being, to escape.
name: A Murder of Crows

description:
As Swamp Thing continues his journey across space, he arrives at the plant world J586. The plant life here are already sentient, and Swamp Thing unknowingly merges with them. Green Lantern Medphyll of Sector 586 eventually finds a solution, sending Swamp Thing on his way.

Meanwhile, Adam Strange finally delivers his message from Swamp Thing to Abby, but her reaction is hysterical and of disbelief.

Includes 2 pinups, the first by Bill Sienkiewicz and the second by Walt Simonson.
name: All Flesh is Grass

Swamp Thing disappears, leaving Abby alone and pregnant in the swamp...and facing forces from an alien invasion.

Note: Swamp Thing only appears in a dream sequence.

description:
Abby faces some definite horrors in a visit to see Matt and is forced to make a most painful decision.

Abby having in the last issue received notice that she would no longer be receiving government benefits is reminded of her ex-husband, Matthew Cable. She visits him at the hospital he is at and is notified that during the time he has been there his bills, have accrued to an incredible amount. Also while she is there realizes however evil he had been, Matt in his comatose state, is now being victimized and ravaged by the hospital and staff that is supposed to care for him. She decides to try to end his suffering.

Within the issue glimpses of Matt in a dreamlike world are shown. Here he goes through a self discovery aided by Dream of the Endless (Morpheus). Ultimately he is freed from the grasp of the machines just as Abigail was ready to pull the plug. He pulls himself free from his lifelines and ask Abigail for forgiveness, then dies; not before giving her his blessing for having found someone else to treat her better than he and love her.

Note: Swamp Thing does not appear in this issue.
name: Final Payment

description:
The bayou is haunted...and these ghosts could have a profound effect on Swamp Thing, Abby, and the baby.

Abigail and Alec Holland visit Matt's final resting place in a cemetery. Elsewhere a man named Adras who is revealed to be a previous Traiteur (medicine man) arrives home to find his wife, Dorisca has passed away. Devastated he subconsciously places a powerful spell over Louisiana whilst grieving for his wife. The effects are felt all over the state and draw the attention of both Swamp Thing and Labo. He tries to return things to a time in the past where he was happy with his wife and inadvertently converts Louisiana to a time before industry took over the swamps.

They both head to Adras to stop the unnatural occurrences from happening. When they arrive the make him realize what he is doing. Dorisca comes back to life like he had hoped but instead she convinces him to stop what he is doing and let nature take its course. In the end he buries her and mourns.
name: La Terre qui Disparait

description: One hundred issues of the best in horror and fantasy are celebrated in this special 52-page issue of Swamp Thing. Len Wein and Bernie Wrightson's creation of the crusading Earth elemental reaches a milestone that sees Swamp Thing's daughter, Tefe, in a devil of a situation. Tefe has been kidnapped by the demons of the underworld, and Swamp Thing is on a mission to find the powerful water that will enable him to communicate with any other living being - including demons. Only then will he be able to find his lost daughter who is now an amorphous, bodiless being. The mysterious Parliament of Trees holds the history of the Earth elementals. Its location is the legendary Garden of Eden, now found on the forbidding wasteland of Antarctica. Swamp Thing #100 delves into Swamp Thing's fight with the guardian angel of the Garden, an encounter with a missing elemental - and his search for Tefe.
name: Tales of Eden

description:
Scot Eaton debuts as the new penciller in "A Child's Garden." Tefe has become a problem child, so Swamp Thing visits the Parliament of Trees for advice. But the kidnapper Bad Man may end Tefe's life before her father's return. Guest-starring Matthew the Raven from SANDMAN.

Note: Morpheus' appearance is off-panel but his speech bubble is seen when he calls Matthew. Sugar & Spike appear in an imaginary sequence along with famous literary characters.
name: A Child's Garden

Swamp Thing must battle his own daughter...to save her life!

description: Part 1 of the 4-part 'Bad Gumbo': The entire Swamp Thing mythos is turned inside out when Dr. Alec Holland regains consciousness in a South American hospital, sweating and disoriented from a terrible nightmare in which he had shambled through swamps as the reigning Earth Elemental. Then he remembers the truth: He overdosed on organic hallucinogens during one of his experiments in plant chemistry and has been experiencing fever dreams ever since. Yet Holland can't shake the strange connection he feels to the silver-haired woman named Abigail Arcane...or to the savage, murderous Swamp Thing rumored to the rampaging through the Louisiana bayou, killing anyone who crosses his path.
name: Vegetable Man

description:
Returning to Louisiana, Swamp Thing meets Anna, a mysterious writer with a book of short stories-tales into which the Earth Elemental is irresistibly drawn‚Ä¶one by one.

Swamp Thing encounters a woman named Anna in the Mississippi River, who claims to be the ghost of a tormented writer who committed suicide. She's now trapped inside her unpublished and uncompleted book of short stories, River Run. Each story inside it branches off into an alternate world at certain points of the Mississippi, showing worlds that might've been had history occurred differently. But none of the stories have been able to run correctly, because they lack an element which ties them together. Anna believes that Swamp Thing is supposed to be that element, so he agrees to enter her literary world to help her rest in peace.
name: River Run Prologue: Flotsam and Jetsam

description:
‚ÄúRiver Run‚Äù begins as Swamp Thing enters the first in a series of fictional worlds created by the mysterious Anna. Transported to a gothic horror version of New Orleans, he encounters Harry Moon, a hard-bitten private eye whose beat includes chasing down vampires, monsters‚Ä¶and Earth Elementals.

In the first story of River Run, City of the Dead, Swamp Thing enters a New Orleans where magic and the occult are part of everyday life. He must help the local law enforcement track down a de-evolving man responsible for a string of murders.

Note: This chapter seems similar to what would be the earth-13 concept in the post-Flashpoint multiverse.
name: City of the Dead: Chapter One of River Run

description:
‚ÄúRiver Run‚Äù continues: Swamp Thing arrives in an alternative America-one in which the Nazis won World War II, where he is offered the chance to avenge millions of murdered souls.

In the second story of River Run, Twilight of the Gods, Swamp Thing now enters a world where Nazi Germany has taken over the world, and Alois Hitler is married to Norma Jean Baker. Using Jewish occult magic, Swamp Thing is summoned as a golem by the American President, who wants to use the elemental to wipe out the world in a mass genocide, rather then have a world that was born out of the extinction of over a dozen races carry on. But, Swamp Thing points out that one genocide can't make up for another, so the President destroys Swamp Thing's body. But, he didn't dispose of it properly, and the true spirit of justice carries out said genocide.

Note: This chapter is inspired in the earth-x concept from the pre-crisis multiverse.
name: Twilight of the Gods: Chapter Two of River Run

description:
‚ÄúRiver Run‚Äù continues as Swamp Thing visits a world where Alec Holland is merely a botanist working to create a bio-restorative formula-but death still haunts the swamp.

In the fifth story of River Run, Darker Genesis, Swamp Thing meets an Alec Holland who never became Swamp Thing, whose wife Linda was never murdered, and they have a daughter named Anna. It's now up to Swamp Thing to make sure his counterpart does not suffer the same tragedy that made him what he is today, but someone must take his place in this world. What's a plant elemental to do?

Note: This chapter is inspired in the earth-prime concept from the pre-crisis multiverse.
name: Darker Genesis: Chapter Five of River Run

description:
The story of Anna, who has led Swamp Thing into a dizzying journey through alternative worlds, is revealed in the penultimate chapter of 'River Run.'

In the sixth story of River Run, Sink of Swim, the origin of Anna, Swamp Thing's ghostly damsel-in-distress, is revealed.

Anna had an okay life. She made a living writing comic books, plenty of money, and a hot boyfriend who did all her cooking and cleaning. That was all until she received a chain letter in the mail. When she ignores it, that's when her bad luck starts. Her publishers go bankrupt, her bank accounts are wiped clean, her boyfriend disappears in the bathtub, her house gets flooded, and she's pregnant. When she moves in with her sister and gets an abortion, Anna's horrified when her hand turns into water. At the same time, her sister get's run down by a hit-and-run driver. Left all alone, Anna has nothing left but to finish her book, River Run, but after too many expired deadlines no in interested anymore. So, she tries to kill herself with an overdose, but she uses allergy medicine by mistake. On her second attempt, she swallows a cup filled with a dozen different types of household cleaning chemicals. That does the trick.

With both Anna and Swamp Thing done with the last story, Anna dissolves into water that gets sucked into a sewer grate. Swamp Thing picks up her book, and discovers a seventh story. Anna and the Parliament of Waves.
name: Sink or Swim: Chapter Six of River Run

description:
An increasingly alienated Swamp Thing gets some ominous hints about his future from an eerie group of half-alive Cajun tree-men. Meanwhile, Nightmaster faces what may be his last stand against the warlocks who have destroyed his home dimension.

The issue features the various sword and sorcery characters of DC in a story which is completed in the following issue and retcons them to be being mental constructs of Nightmaster. The retconn was poorly received and was ignored by later writers.
name: Trees of Knowledge

description: Comics legend Curt Swan guest-pencils the most off-beat SWAMP THING story of recent years. When lovable hippie Chester Williams forsakes his left-wing past for the ultraconservative life of a New York City cop, the powers that be decide he's just the man to talk the Swamp Thing out of his environmentally-conscious plans for humankind. Is it an imaginary story...or a frightening glimpse of America's future?

description: 'Trial by Fire,' part 1 of 6. Beginning Mark Millar's climactic 6-part Swamp Thing storyline! A year has passed since the Swamp Thing was last seen, and the U.S. government sends Jason Woodrue, the man who discovered Swamp Thing's true nature, to navigate the now-unearthly landscape of the Louisiana bayou in search of the Earth Elemental. But Swamp Thing may be as altered as his environment...and John Constantine and the Phantom Stranger have their own plans for dealing with what he's become.
name: Trial by Fire, Part 1: Golden Days Before the End

description:
‚ÄúRiver Run‚Äù continues: moving deeper into the worlds of Anna's book, Swamp Thing's loyalties are tested when he meets Abigail Arcane, an evil young woman who's come to live with her kindly Uncle Anton.

In the third story of River Run, The Bad Seed, Swamp Thing meets an alternate version of Abby Arcane, living on an Iowa farm with her uncle Anton Arcane, his wife Anna, and their son Joey. But, this world's version of Abby is nothing like the version Swamp Thing knows, and she has a few ugly surprises in store for her relatives.

Note: This chapter is inspired in the earth-3 concept from the pre-crisis multiverse.
name: The Bad Seed: Chapter Three of River Run

description:
A boy finds and plants one of Swamp Thing's discarded bodies...and from it, something monstrous grows.

Story of a young boy named Casey and his troubled family life and the refuge he finds in the growing shell of an abandoned Swamp Thing body.

Note: Swamp Thing's appearance in this issue is cover only.
name: The Growing Season
